hands, feet, tails, brains, locomotion, feeding, social systems, forms of communication, and mating strategies. Primatologist Alfred Rosenberger, one of the foremost experts on these mammals, explains their fascinating adaptations and how they came about.New World Monkeys provides a dramatic picture of the sixteen living genera of New World monkeys and a fossil record that shows that their ancestors have lived in the same ecological niches for up to 20 million years-only to now find themselves imperiled by the extinction crisis. Rosenberger also challenges the argument that these primates originally came to South America from Africa by floating across the Atlantic on a raft of vegetation some 45 million years ago. He explains that they are more likely to have crossed via a landbridge that once connected Western Europe and Canada at a time when many tropical mammals transferred between the northern continents.Based on the most current findings, New World Monkeys offers the first synthesis of decades of fieldwork and laboratory and museum research conducted by hundreds of scientists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNew World monkeysxEvolution. 0aPrimatesxAdaptation. 0aPrimatology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Primatology.2bisacsh  aAmazon.  aAmazonian rainforest.  aAtlantic Forest.  aadaptive zones.  aanimal communication.  aanimal tool use.  aatelidae.  abehavior.  abrain size evolution.  acapuchin.  acebidae.  aconservation.  adiets.  aecology.  aendangered species.  aevolutionary biology.  aevolutionary models.  afolivores.  afrugivores.  ainsectivores.  alifestyles.  amarmosets.  amating.  amolecular clock.  amuriqui.  aneotropical mammals.  aopposable thumbs.  apaleontology.  aphylogeny.  apithecidae.  aplatyrrhines.  aprehensile tails.